[ Indistinct conversations ]

02:31.639 --> 02:35.274
Virginia: I certainly hope that
you didn't tip him.

02:35.309 --> 02:36.642
William:
Of course I tipped him.

02:36.644 --> 02:37.976
Virginia:
Who gets into a taxi

02:37.978 --> 02:39.728
and says,
"We're from out of town.

02:39.780 --> 02:41.446
Take whatever route you'd like"?

02:41.482 --> 02:43.732
The man drove us
through Brooklyn, Bill.

02:43.784 --> 02:45.417
William:
Ah, so what if he did?

02:45.452 --> 02:47.986
It was worth the extra $2
to get a view of that skyline,

02:47.988 --> 02:49.238
don't you think?

02:49.290 --> 02:51.623
Virginia: No, I don't.

02:51.659 --> 02:54.993
William: Betty said that <i> The Times
</i> gave this place four stars.

02:54.995 --> 02:57.045
Apparently, it's nearly
impossible to get a reservation.

02:57.131 --> 02:58.664
Virginia: Well,
I would've been just as happy

02:58.716 --> 03:00.499
to order a BLT from room service
and call it a night.

03:00.551 --> 03:02.417
William: Nonsense.

03:02.469 --> 03:04.586
Today went just about as well
as it could possibly have gone.

03:04.638 --> 03:06.922
I say you and I have
more than earned ourselves

03:06.974 --> 03:08.590
a five-course dinner.

03:08.642 --> 03:12.094
Virginia: Well, that is
very generous of you to say.

03:12.146 --> 03:14.680
Because given how you
monopolized that meeting,

03:14.732 --> 03:16.014
the most I've earned,
I would think,

03:16.066 --> 03:17.616
would be a dinner roll
and a butter pat.

03:17.651 --> 03:19.952
William: Virginia,
can't you let it go, please?

03:19.987 --> 03:22.487
It all worked out.
Let's enjoy the evening.

03:22.523 --> 03:24.489
Colette: - May I take your coats?
William: - Yes, thank you.

03:24.525 --> 03:26.491
Virginia: I'll keep mine,
thank you very much.

03:26.527 --> 03:27.693
William: Are you sure?
I think you'll be more comfortable--

03:27.728 --> 03:29.111
Virginia:
Is this yet another thing

03:29.163 --> 03:30.495
you would like
to overrule me on?

03:31.866 --> 03:33.298
William: The lady will be
keeping her coat.

03:33.334 --> 03:35.868
Virginia: In case
I throw a drink in his face

03:35.870 --> 03:39.171
and need to make a speedy exit,
which is entirely possible.

03:39.206 --> 03:41.757
William: Why don't I give
our name to the-- to the host?

03:43.711 --> 03:45.294
Virginia:
What is the fastest

03:45.346 --> 03:47.713
you've ever seen someone
get through a meal here?

03:47.748 --> 03:49.514
Maitre D':
Masters, you say?

03:49.550 --> 03:51.583
I'm not seeing anything
in the book, sir.

03:51.619 --> 03:53.468
Are you sure your reservation
was for tonight?

03:53.520 --> 03:55.354
William: Quite sure.
Can I take a...

03:55.389 --> 03:56.521
Virginia:
Is there a problem?

03:56.557 --> 03:57.723
William:
There it is. That's us.

03:57.775 --> 03:59.424
Maitre D':
Mosher, party of four?

03:59.460 --> 04:01.226
William:
Well, Mosher, Masters--

04:01.228 --> 04:03.395
if it was a bad connection,
someone could've easily misu--

04:03.447 --> 04:06.148
Mosher. Mas--
See?

04:06.200 --> 04:08.400
Virginia:
Bill, that is entirely possible

04:08.402 --> 04:10.869
if you were calling
from a submarine.

04:10.905 --> 04:13.238
And "two" doesn't sound anything
like "four."

04:13.274 --> 04:15.540
- We are a party of two.
Maitre D': - I'm confused, sir.

04:15.609 --> 04:17.993
Didn't you say that yours
was a party of four?

04:18.045 --> 04:19.745
William: I did.
No, we're four, Virginia--

04:19.797 --> 04:21.245
you, me, and the Logans.

04:21.298 --> 04:25.751
Her name's Alice, isn't it?
Uh, Dan's wife?

04:29.890 --> 04:31.423
Man: <i> What are you doing in</i>
<i>the lab at this hour of night?</i>

04:31.425 --> 04:32.891
Jenny: [ Laughs ]

04:32.927 --> 04:34.092
Man: <i> And what's</i>
<i>all that noise going on?</i>

04:34.161 --> 04:36.094
[ Libby gasps, Paul chuckles ]

04:36.146 --> 04:37.896
Libby: Not while
the children are awake.

04:37.932 --> 04:39.147
Paul: Oh, come on.

04:41.402 --> 04:43.735
Libby: All right, kitty cats,
it's time for bed.

04:43.771 --> 04:45.938
Jenny: 10 more minutes.

04:45.990 --> 04:47.606
Libby: You said that
20 minutes ago.

04:47.608 --> 04:49.274
Johnny: Yeah,
but it's almost over.

04:49.276 --> 04:51.076
Paul: Come on, Lib.
Just let them watch the end.

04:51.111 --> 04:52.361
- It's fine.
- [ Children laughing ]

04:52.413 --> 04:53.612
Libby: You know,
for a football coach,

04:53.664 --> 04:54.947
you are a bit of a pushover.

04:54.949 --> 04:56.281
Paul: - Oh, really?
Libby: - Mm-hmm.

04:56.283 --> 04:57.616
Paul:
Okay. Come on, guys.

04:57.618 --> 04:58.917
You heard your mother.
It's bedtime.

04:58.953 --> 05:00.419
Hup, hup. Let's go.
Set goes off.

05:00.454 --> 05:01.703
Ice-cream bowls in the kitchen.

05:01.755 --> 05:02.955
Johnny,
I want to see some hustle.

05:03.007 --> 05:04.456
Jenn, put some pep in your step.
Come on.

05:06.126 --> 05:07.426
Libby: Mr. Edley's kidding.

05:07.461 --> 05:09.761
But 10 more minutes,
and that is it.

05:09.797 --> 05:11.296
No more negotiating.

05:11.332 --> 05:12.547
Johnny: - Okay.
Jenny: - Okay.

05:12.599 --> 05:14.967
[ Children laugh ]

05:15.002 --> 05:18.637
Paul: However you want me to be,
I'll be.

05:18.639 --> 05:20.222
[ Chuckles ]

05:20.274 --> 05:22.724
Virginia: She's joining--
they're joining us?

05:22.776 --> 05:24.309
William: Why do you look
so surprised?

05:24.311 --> 05:25.978
- We discussed this.
Virginia: - We did not.

05:27.481 --> 05:29.014
William: - Are you certain?
Virginia: - Quite certain.

05:29.049 --> 05:31.483
Absolutely cer-- I've never been
more certain of anything

05:31.485 --> 05:32.951
in my life.

05:32.987 --> 05:34.319
William: Well, maybe--
Ah, you know what?

05:34.321 --> 05:36.321
I-- I mentioned it to Betty.

05:36.373 --> 05:38.573
That's right. I did.
I must've forgotten.

05:38.625 --> 05:40.292
Maitre D':
I'm sorry, Dr. Masters.

05:40.327 --> 05:43.295
Is it possible you thought
you made a reservation

05:43.330 --> 05:45.163
in the same way you thought
you told your wife

05:45.215 --> 05:46.298
about your dining companions?

05:46.333 --> 05:47.833
Virginia:
I am not his wife.

05:47.835 --> 05:50.085
Mosher:
Mosher, party of four.

05:50.137 --> 05:52.504
Maitre d': Good evening, Mr. Mosher.
Right this way, sir.

05:52.556 --> 05:53.972
Deirdre will take you
to your table.

05:54.008 --> 05:55.757
Virginia:
What is going on here, Bill?

05:55.809 --> 05:58.010
William: - What do you mean?
Virginia: - What are you up to?

05:58.045 --> 06:02.514
Why would you ask Dan
and his wife to join us?

06:02.566 --> 06:04.850
You've barely even
said two words to him

06:04.918 --> 06:06.818
since he set foot
in our office.

06:06.854 --> 06:09.821
You've rejected any social
overtures he's made to you.

06:09.857 --> 06:11.356
You've barely even tolerated
the research

06:11.392 --> 06:12.524
that he asked us to conduct.

06:12.526 --> 06:14.359
William:
Which was unfair of me.

06:15.863 --> 06:17.062
Virginia: It was?

06:17.097 --> 06:18.663
William: Absolutely.

06:18.699 --> 06:20.866
Virginia,
I was threatened by him.

06:20.918 --> 06:23.368
I see that now.

06:23.370 --> 06:24.836
What are you doing?

06:24.872 --> 06:26.955
Virginia: Looking for
that bald man on TV

06:27.007 --> 06:28.790
who pops out
with his hidden camera.

06:28.842 --> 06:31.293
William: [ Sighs ]

06:31.345 --> 06:33.178
I thought he was taking up
too much of our time.

06:33.213 --> 06:34.413
Virginia: <i> "Our</i> time?"

06:34.448 --> 06:36.298
William:
All right,<i> your</i> time.

06:36.350 --> 06:38.633
I didn't like
having to indulge his curiosity,

06:38.685 --> 06:40.385
which was shortsighted of me.

06:40.421 --> 06:43.221
So what if his projects
didn't amount to anything?

06:43.273 --> 06:44.973
The man opened his checkbook
to us.

06:45.025 --> 06:47.192
Now we have a book contract
to show for it.

06:47.227 --> 06:49.811
So I thought it was the right
thing to do to show him a--

06:49.863 --> 06:52.764
you know, a little appreciation
for the support he's given us.

06:54.568 --> 06:57.536
Virginia: Well, that's...

06:57.571 --> 06:58.837
Huh.

06:58.872 --> 07:00.322
William: Well,
it's not awkward for you

07:00.374 --> 07:01.990
that I invited his wife along,
is it?

07:02.042 --> 07:03.909
Virginia:
Why would that be awkward?

07:03.944 --> 07:05.911
William: I'm asking you.

07:05.946 --> 07:08.747
Virginia: And I'm answering...
rhetorically.

07:08.749 --> 07:12.050
No, it's not awkward, Bill,
unless you've imagined us

07:12.086 --> 07:13.752
having to eat standing up
in the coatroom.

07:13.754 --> 07:15.003
William: [ Chuckles ]

07:15.055 --> 07:16.338
Virginia:
While you figure this out,

07:16.390 --> 07:18.223
I'm going to go freshen up.

07:18.258 --> 07:19.891
Maitre D': Shall I have Colette
check this for you?

07:19.927 --> 07:22.427
Virginia: You are not
to check that coat, Bill.

07:22.463 --> 07:24.930
William:
The lady will hang on to it.

07:32.106 --> 07:33.271
Johnny: You're still here?

07:33.323 --> 07:34.606
Paul: Hey, Johnny.

07:34.608 --> 07:36.358
Uh, yeah,
I noticed the light was out,

07:36.410 --> 07:39.945
so I thought I'd fix it
before I went home to my house.

07:39.997 --> 07:41.446
Johnny: Where's my mom?

07:41.498 --> 07:43.248
Paul: Your mom is in
reading to Jenny.

07:43.283 --> 07:45.784
Johnny: Um...

07:47.421 --> 07:50.455
Could you-- could you maybe
help me with something

07:50.457 --> 07:52.057
- in my room?
Paul: - Of course.

07:52.092 --> 07:54.159
- Absolutely.
Johnny: - Bring the ladder.

07:54.194 --> 07:57.429
Paul: Bring the ladder?
Okay.

07:57.464 --> 07:59.381
All right. Let's go.

07:59.433 --> 08:01.933
[ Toilet flushes ]

08:05.772 --> 08:07.973
Daphne: - Good evening, ma'am.
Virginia: - Good evening.

08:07.975 --> 08:09.274
Daphne: May I offer you
something, ma'am?

08:09.309 --> 08:10.976
Virginia: No, thank you.

08:11.028 --> 08:12.611
Daphne: Are you sure?

08:12.646 --> 08:14.779
We have some lovely new scents
as well as the classics.

08:14.815 --> 08:15.947
Channel.

08:15.983 --> 08:17.983
Virginia:
I think that's Chanel.

08:17.985 --> 08:19.618
Daphne: Oh, is it?
I don't speak French.

08:19.653 --> 08:23.655
This one's new, Promesse,
and we have Ambush by Dana.

08:23.690 --> 08:27.459
Virginia: That would certainly
be appropriate to the occasion.

08:27.494 --> 08:29.127
Alice: - Excuse me?
Daphne: - Yes?

08:29.163 --> 08:31.079
Alice: Uh, there--
there's no paper in here.

08:31.131 --> 08:32.664
- Would you mind--
Daphne: - Oh! Oh, gosh!

08:32.666 --> 08:33.965
I'm so sorry, ma'am.
Right away.

08:34.001 --> 08:36.001
Uh, um, there you go.

08:36.053 --> 08:37.635
I should've checked the stall
beforehand.

08:37.671 --> 08:40.804
Alice: - It's all right.
Daphne: - Oh, gosh.

08:40.841 --> 08:42.256
See? I'm still learning.

08:42.308 --> 08:44.426
They usually have me
answering the phones,

08:44.478 --> 08:46.344
but Carol Anne,
the girl who's usually here,

08:46.346 --> 08:48.013
she slipped in the kitchen
two days ago

08:48.065 --> 08:49.481
and knocked out her two
front teeth, got a black eye,

08:49.516 --> 08:51.183
and they won't let her
back to work

08:51.185 --> 08:52.851
'cause it looks like
her boyfriend beat her up.

08:52.853 --> 08:54.603
You can't have that in
a nice place like this, right?

08:54.655 --> 08:56.271
Ambush you said?
[ Perfume sprays ]

08:56.323 --> 08:57.772
Virginia: - What are you doing?
Daphne: - Didn't you--

08:57.824 --> 08:59.357
Virginia: No,
I s-- I said no thank you.

08:59.409 --> 09:00.825
Daphne:
Oh, I'm so sorry, ma'am.

09:00.861 --> 09:01.993
Virginia: May I have
a wet towel, please?

09:02.029 --> 09:03.361
Daphne: Yes.

09:03.413 --> 09:04.613
Oh.

09:06.917 --> 09:08.867
Here.

09:08.919 --> 09:10.785
Hey, you don't like it?
It's not so bad.

09:10.837 --> 09:13.955
Virginia: It's the--
The gentleman that I'm seeing,

09:14.007 --> 09:17.876
he-- he has an aversion to me
wearing fragrances of any kind.

09:17.928 --> 09:19.711
Daphne: An aversion?
Allergies, you mean?

09:19.763 --> 09:22.881
Virginia: No, no. It's-- he
has, uh, a very sensitive nose.

09:22.883 --> 09:24.466
[ Toilet flushes ]

09:24.518 --> 09:28.053
Occupational hazard.
It's fine. I'll live. Thank you.

09:28.055 --> 09:29.354
[ Restroom door opens, closes ]

09:35.896 --> 09:37.395
Paul: Did I get him?

09:37.447 --> 09:39.698
Johnny: Uh, no,
he's over there now. See him?

09:39.733 --> 09:40.732
Paul: - Where?
Johnny: - Quick!

09:40.734 --> 09:41.866
Paul: Oh.

09:41.902 --> 09:43.985
- Got him.
Johnny: - Are you sure?

09:44.037 --> 09:46.154
Paul: Flat as a pancake.
You want to see?

09:46.206 --> 09:48.240
Johnny: No, that's okay.
I trust you.

09:48.242 --> 09:49.708
Paul: Come on.

09:49.743 --> 09:53.161
Johnny: I'm not afraid of them
or anything.

09:53.213 --> 09:55.163
Just don't like them.

09:55.215 --> 09:57.215
Paul: I get it.

09:57.251 --> 09:58.750
Is there anything else
you're not too fond of?

09:58.802 --> 10:01.586
Johnny:
I don't really like thunder.

10:01.638 --> 10:03.822
Paul:
Oh, well, come on.

10:04.157 --> 10:06.481
Does anyone like thunder,
really? An

10:06.482 --> 10:09.113
Maybe timpanists, you know?

10:09.205 --> 10:11.781
In the orchestras,
with the big drums?

10:11.782 --> 10:13.254
They probably like it.

10:13.255 --> 10:15.288
You're probably right.

10:15.294 --> 10:17.691
You know what I'm afraid of,
Johnny?

10:17.743 --> 10:18.942
Johnny: What?

10:18.944 --> 10:22.529
Paul: Letting people see
that I'm afraid.

10:22.581 --> 10:24.414
It's like,
what are they gonna think?

10:24.449 --> 10:26.149
This big, tough
football coach--

10:26.185 --> 10:27.584
every time
he goes to the doctor,

10:27.619 --> 10:28.985
he's got to shut his eyes
and whistle a tune

10:29.021 --> 10:30.587
when he gets a shot.

10:30.622 --> 10:32.205
Johnny: - You do that?
Paul: - [ Chuckling ] Yeah.

10:32.257 --> 10:34.257
Every single time.

10:34.293 --> 10:38.128
Here.
You play the doctor.

10:38.180 --> 10:40.130
I'll play me. All right?

10:40.132 --> 10:41.765
Johnny: - Okay.
Paul: - All right.

10:41.800 --> 10:43.216
Johnny: Time for your shot,
Mr. Edley. Are you ready?

10:43.268 --> 10:44.568
Paul: I guess.

10:44.603 --> 10:46.770
[ Whistling ]

10:46.805 --> 10:49.389
[ Groaning ]

10:49.441 --> 10:51.141
Johnny: [ Chuckles ]

10:51.143 --> 10:53.393
Paul: [ Laughs ]

10:53.445 --> 10:55.896
Now, look, you said you weren't
gonna tell anybody, right?

10:55.981 --> 10:57.447
Johnny: - I promise.
Paul: - All right.

10:57.482 --> 10:58.815
Johnny:
And you won't tell mine?

10:58.867 --> 11:00.650
Paul:
I won't tell a soul.

11:00.702 --> 11:03.737
All right.
Get some sleep.

11:03.789 --> 11:06.072
Johnny: - Good night, Mr. Edley.
Paul: - Good night, Johnny.

11:09.962 --> 11:11.962
Dan: Well, I'm sorry you didn't
have my girl make the reservation.

11:11.997 --> 11:13.663
I have some pull here.

11:13.715 --> 11:16.299
I invested in Gordon's place
in Midtown a few years back.

11:16.335 --> 11:18.969
Excuse me,
could you tell Chef Ostroff

11:19.004 --> 11:21.421
that Dan Logan is
with the Masters party--

11:21.473 --> 11:22.672
that's the reservation
that's gone missing--

11:22.724 --> 11:24.174
and ask if
he can accommodate us?

11:24.226 --> 11:26.142
William: Apparently,
they're booked until--

11:26.178 --> 11:28.178
Dan: And that we're very much looking
forward to the tartare tonight.

11:28.180 --> 11:30.013
It's not on the menu,
but they make it when I ask.

11:30.065 --> 11:33.516
Virginia: - Dan? Nice to see you.
Dan: - Virginia.

11:33.518 --> 11:34.935
Virginia: You're alone?

11:34.987 --> 11:37.437
Dan: Uh, Alice is on her way
from uptown.

11:37.489 --> 11:40.273
I must say, Virginia, I wasn't
expecting your invitation.

11:40.359 --> 11:42.125
Virginia: The invitation
didn't come from me.

11:42.160 --> 11:44.027
Dan: Oh, well, my secretary said
a woman called, so I assumed.

11:44.079 --> 11:45.445
That wasn't you?
Then who--

11:45.497 --> 11:47.230
Virginia: Bill, uh,
did you have Betty

11:47.266 --> 11:48.398
make these arrangements?

11:48.433 --> 11:50.400
William: Why, yes, I did.

11:50.435 --> 11:51.785
Why don't I have them
check that?

11:51.837 --> 11:53.003
Dan: Okay.

11:54.706 --> 11:56.840
Thank you.

11:56.875 --> 11:58.959
Virginia: - I am so sorry.
Dan: - Mm-hmm.

11:59.011 --> 12:00.877
Virginia:
I had absolutely no idea.

12:00.879 --> 12:03.797
Bill orchestrated this
entire thing without telling me.

12:03.849 --> 12:05.582
Why would you bring your wife?

12:05.617 --> 12:08.551
Dan: Because when the invitation
came in, presumably from you,

12:08.604 --> 12:10.353
my secretary called Alice
to confirm the time

12:10.389 --> 12:11.805
without consulting me.

12:11.857 --> 12:13.356
- And there you are.
Alice: - Hello, darling.

12:13.392 --> 12:15.475
Dan: Mm. You made it.

12:15.527 --> 12:16.726
I would like to introduce you
to--

12:16.778 --> 12:18.812
Virginia: Virginia Johnson.
Hello.

12:18.864 --> 12:20.647
Alice: Finally.
I'm so glad you called.

12:20.699 --> 12:22.866
Danny just thinks
the world of you.

12:22.901 --> 12:24.234
Talks about you nonstop.

12:24.286 --> 12:25.902
Virginia: Is that right?

12:25.904 --> 12:28.004
Alice: And, my goodness,
you're just a slip of a thing.

12:28.040 --> 12:31.041
I-I don't know why I always imagined
you'd be much bigger boned.

12:31.076 --> 12:32.909
William:
Mrs. Logan, I presume.

12:32.911 --> 12:35.412
Alice: - Alice, please.
William: - Bill Masters.

12:35.464 --> 12:37.914
I'm just delighted that you
and your husband could join us.

12:37.966 --> 12:40.183
Now, there has been a little
snafu with the reservation

12:40.218 --> 12:42.052
- that we're working out.
Maitre D': - Mr. Logan,

12:42.087 --> 12:44.671
I am so sorry to keep you
and your party waiting.

12:44.723 --> 12:48.058
We have a table for you
if you will follow Jacques.

12:48.093 --> 12:52.228
Dan: Ladies?

12:52.264 --> 12:55.432
It's all who you know, Bill.

12:55.434 --> 12:57.267
William: Whom.

12:57.269 --> 12:58.401
It's whom.

13:01.239 --> 13:03.106
Alice: Uh,
this is a table for two.

13:03.108 --> 13:04.741
Virginia:
We're a party of four.

13:04.776 --> 13:06.943
William: Well, five,
if you include the coat.

13:06.995 --> 13:09.112
And may I ask,
where do you sit your patrons

13:09.164 --> 13:11.031
who don't have pull--
the scullery?

13:11.083 --> 13:12.615
Jacques: [ French accent ]
I'm terribly sorry.

13:12.668 --> 13:15.869
This is the only table we have
available at the moment.

13:15.921 --> 13:17.954
Dan: Perhaps we should wait
for something else to open up.

13:17.956 --> 13:19.956
Jacques: I'm afraid
we are fully booked, sir.

13:20.008 --> 13:21.374
Virginia:
Or come back another time.

13:21.426 --> 13:23.209
William:
Oh, don't be silly.

13:23.261 --> 13:25.378
We can all squeeze in.
Can't we, Alice?

13:25.430 --> 13:27.213
Alice: Absolutely.
It'll be cozy.

13:31.603 --> 13:32.802
Jacques:
You're sure I can't check--

13:32.804 --> 13:34.471
Virginia:
I'm quite sure, thank you.

13:38.143 --> 13:41.277
Jacques: May I get you started
with a cocktail? Ladies?

13:41.313 --> 13:43.279
Virginia:
A Manhattan, please.

13:43.315 --> 13:44.914
Dan: Alice?

13:44.950 --> 13:47.400
So, she'll have a tonic water
with a squeeze of--

13:47.452 --> 13:48.485
Alice:
Uh, white wine, please.

13:48.487 --> 13:49.986
Dan: But, honey--

13:50.021 --> 13:51.654
Alice: I'd like a glass
of white wine, Dan.

13:51.656 --> 13:53.490
Do you have an objection
to that?

13:53.492 --> 13:55.959
Dan: Why don't we make it
a spritzer?

13:55.994 --> 13:58.828
William: First,
uh, can I suggest

13:58.880 --> 14:01.998
that we start with a bottle
of your finest champagne?

14:02.000 --> 14:03.249
We're celebrating.

14:03.301 --> 14:05.168
Alice: Ooh.

14:07.472 --> 14:09.973
Libby:
What are you doing?

14:10.008 --> 14:13.009
Paul:
It was slow to drain, so...

14:13.044 --> 14:14.594
What?

14:14.646 --> 14:17.013
Libby: You can't fix everything
in the house.

14:17.065 --> 14:19.449
He's only gone two days.
He's gonna come back and notice.

14:19.484 --> 14:21.684
Paul: Oh, really?
Bill's gonna notice?

14:21.737 --> 14:24.104
Come on.

14:24.156 --> 14:26.823
Libby: Well,
you do have to be more careful

14:26.858 --> 14:28.441
in front of the kids.

14:28.493 --> 14:31.611
You can't take my hand
under the dining-room table

14:31.663 --> 14:33.496
or reach under my skirt.

14:33.532 --> 14:34.664
Paul:
Oh, they didn't see that.

14:34.699 --> 14:37.784
Libby:
But they could have.

14:37.836 --> 14:40.036
You can't call me Lib
in front of them, either.

14:40.038 --> 14:41.337
Paul: - Did I do that?
Libby: - Mm-hmm.

14:41.373 --> 14:42.672
Paul: Oh.

14:42.707 --> 14:44.290
Libby: You know,
"pass the ketchup, Lib.

14:44.342 --> 14:46.176
Those potatoes were delicious, Lib."

14:46.211 --> 14:47.844
Paul: All right.
I have this fantasy, okay?

14:47.879 --> 14:50.130
Now, don't laugh at me,
but I have this fantasy

14:50.182 --> 14:53.133
that, you know, the kids
will start calling me Paul.

14:53.185 --> 14:57.020
Not right away, but just
eventually, you know?

14:57.055 --> 14:58.688
You know how Howie has
that thing with "L's"?

14:58.723 --> 15:01.224
Libby: I secretly hope
he never loses it.

15:01.226 --> 15:03.693
Paul: I know. Well, if you
drop the "L" off of "Paul,"

15:03.728 --> 15:05.895
that becomes "paw," right?

15:05.947 --> 15:08.898
And then maybe the older kids
start calling me pa,

15:08.900 --> 15:11.568
and then, pretty soon,
that's what I am to them.

15:11.620 --> 15:14.571
You know, their pa.

15:14.623 --> 15:18.408
You wouldn't have a problem
with that, would you?

15:18.460 --> 15:20.910
[ Both chuckle ]

15:29.221 --> 15:30.670
William:
To "Human Sexual Inadequacy."

15:30.722 --> 15:33.256
Dan:
"Human Sexual Inadequacy."

15:33.308 --> 15:35.091
Alice: Do we really want
to toast that?

15:35.093 --> 15:37.343
Dan: It's the name of Bill
and Virginia's next book.

15:37.395 --> 15:38.728
Alice: Oh, I see.

15:38.763 --> 15:40.096
William: [ Chuckles ]

15:40.148 --> 15:42.182
Alice: Well, then,
congratulations, you two.

15:42.234 --> 15:43.766
How exciting.

15:43.819 --> 15:45.351
Dan: After the success
of the first one,

15:45.403 --> 15:46.769
I'm sure this one was
pretty much in the bag.

15:46.822 --> 15:48.238
No hard sell required.

15:48.273 --> 15:50.106
Virginia: Yes,
you'd think, wouldn't you,

15:50.158 --> 15:53.359
that all we needed to do was let
the couples work that we've done

15:53.411 --> 15:54.777
speak for itself.

15:54.779 --> 15:58.031
But Bill felt the need
to up the ante.

15:58.083 --> 15:59.282
William:
Virginia, please, let's not.

15:59.334 --> 16:01.117
Virginia: Oh, let's.

16:01.169 --> 16:03.086
William:
Virginia's upset with me

16:03.121 --> 16:08.091
because I... deviated slightly
from our agreed-upon script.

16:08.126 --> 16:12.045
Virginia: I wouldn't say "deviated,"
and I wouldn't say "slightly."

16:12.097 --> 16:14.714
I'd say that you hijacked
the meeting entirely.

16:14.766 --> 16:15.965
William: [ Chuckles ]

16:15.967 --> 16:17.550
Virginia:
Uh, Bill told them

16:17.602 --> 16:20.136
that we intend to include
a chapter in the next book

16:20.138 --> 16:21.638
on our work with surrogates.

16:21.640 --> 16:23.273
Dan: Mm. I thought
you were phasing that out.

16:23.308 --> 16:25.808
Virginia: Yes, well,
Bill revived it this afternoon

16:25.810 --> 16:29.062
and committed us
to continuing with the program.

16:29.114 --> 16:30.563
William: Only after
the Little Brown team

16:30.615 --> 16:32.448
seemed disinclined
to move forward.

16:32.484 --> 16:34.984
Virginia: Not disinclined,
and even if they were,

16:35.036 --> 16:36.819
that doesn't mean
that you should jump in

16:36.872 --> 16:39.489
and offer up research
that we both decided

16:39.541 --> 16:41.791
to postpone
for the foreseeable future.

16:41.826 --> 16:44.160
William: They never would've committed
to so large an advance, Virginia.

16:44.212 --> 16:46.863
Virginia: [ Sighs ] The last time
that we were short hard evidence

16:46.898 --> 16:48.665
that our research
would yield solid results--

16:48.667 --> 16:52.335
the impotency work-- you argued
that it was wrong to promote it.

16:52.387 --> 16:53.920
Alice: Do most people assume
you're married?

16:53.972 --> 16:55.338
William: [ Chuckles ]

16:55.340 --> 16:58.174
Alice: You seem married.
Don't they seem married?

16:58.226 --> 16:59.676
Dan:
They're not married.

16:59.711 --> 17:01.594
In fact,
Bill has a very lovely wife.

17:01.646 --> 17:03.263
William: Mm, you've met?

17:03.315 --> 17:05.848
Dan: No, but I've seen
her picture on your desk.

17:05.849 --> 17:07.267
You don't bring her along
when you travel?

17:07.319 --> 17:09.852
William: - I don't.
Dan: - Oh, why's that?

17:09.854 --> 17:12.188
Surely she would like a trip
to New York, wouldn't she?

17:12.240 --> 17:14.324
William: Yes, but we do have
three children at home.

17:14.358 --> 17:16.025
Alice:
Oh. Do you have pictures?

17:16.077 --> 17:17.327
William: I don't, no.

17:17.362 --> 17:20.863
Dan: Really? No pictures?
Not a one?

17:20.865 --> 17:23.333
Alice: Dan doesn't like to bring
me on his adventures, either.

17:23.367 --> 17:25.367
William: - Oh, and why's that?
Alice: - I have a theory.

17:25.420 --> 17:28.538
William:
Oh, I would love to hear it.

17:28.590 --> 17:30.340
Dan:
Another breadbasket, please?

17:30.375 --> 17:31.457
Alice: Well, with so many
more women in the workforce,

17:31.509 --> 17:33.376
I think it's easier for a man,

17:33.428 --> 17:35.178
especially one
as handsome as him,

17:35.213 --> 17:38.681
to conduct his business
unencumbered by a wedding ring.

17:38.717 --> 17:40.216
Wouldn't you agree, Virginia?

17:41.770 --> 17:44.087
I'm asking you as a woman.

17:44.122 --> 17:48.308
Virginia:
I really wouldn't know.

17:48.360 --> 17:51.361
Alice: It's not unlike
your approach, Bill.

17:51.396 --> 17:53.980
You tantalize the buyer
with the promise of something

17:54.032 --> 17:56.065
that you may not actually
be able to provide.

17:56.117 --> 17:58.901
I'm not blind.
I know I married a flirt.

17:58.954 --> 18:00.403
William: [ Chuckles ]

18:00.405 --> 18:01.988
Alice: But it got me
a three-bedroom apartment

18:02.040 --> 18:03.823
overlooking
the Museum of Natural History.

18:03.875 --> 18:06.409
Dan: Hey, might want
to slow down a bit, dear.

18:06.444 --> 18:08.077
Alice: Mm.

18:08.079 --> 18:10.046
You might want to stop squeezing
my leg under the table.

18:12.117 --> 18:14.667
What was the name
of the woman in Dallas?

18:14.719 --> 18:16.085
The linen heiress?

18:16.137 --> 18:17.954
Danny sold her on the idea

18:17.989 --> 18:21.758
of including lavender sachets
in her seet shets.

18:23.645 --> 18:24.894
Sheet... sets.

18:24.929 --> 18:26.262
William: [ Chuckles ]

18:26.314 --> 18:27.930
Alice: [ Laughing ]
That's hard to say.

18:27.983 --> 18:30.933
Dan: Especially after
two glasses of champagne.

18:30.935 --> 18:33.353
William: Well,
may I propose another toast?

18:33.405 --> 18:34.687
Alice: - Mm!
Virginia: - I vote no.

18:34.739 --> 18:36.939
Um, I'm sorry.
Was that rhetorical?

18:36.941 --> 18:39.025
Alice: I love your
sense of humor, Virginia.

18:39.077 --> 18:40.743
It's very New York.
Are you Jewish?

18:40.779 --> 18:42.111
William: To you, Dan.

18:42.113 --> 18:44.030
Dan: To me?

18:44.082 --> 18:45.948
William: Well-- well, we could
never have gotten to this point

18:45.950 --> 18:47.617
without your financial support.

18:47.669 --> 18:48.951
Alice: Hm.

18:49.004 --> 18:51.537
Dan: Well, that's, uh...

18:51.589 --> 18:53.423
That's kind of you to say, Bill.

18:53.458 --> 18:54.957
William: Well,
it's absolutely true.

18:54.959 --> 18:56.876
- Isn't it, Virginia?
Virginia: - It is.

18:56.928 --> 18:58.761
Uh, you have kept us afloat.

18:58.797 --> 19:01.631
William:
And I am happy to report

19:01.633 --> 19:04.300
that the advance
we received today

19:04.302 --> 19:07.637
will more than cover our
operational costs from now on.

19:07.639 --> 19:11.641
So we're not just able
to repay you in full.

19:11.643 --> 19:13.109
We're also able
to provide you

19:13.144 --> 19:17.980
with a significant return
on your investment.

19:18.016 --> 19:20.066
Thank you.

19:20.118 --> 19:22.235
To the end of our journey.

19:22.287 --> 19:24.620
Alice: Hear, hear.
[ Chuckles ]

19:24.656 --> 19:27.657
Come on, you two.
To happy endings.

19:27.659 --> 19:29.992
Virginia: So this is yet another
thing you've just decided, Bill,

19:29.994 --> 19:32.412
that our work with Dan is over?

19:32.464 --> 19:34.630
William: Well, isn't it?
I'm sorry. Do you disagree, Dan?

19:34.666 --> 19:36.666
You made an investment.

19:36.718 --> 19:39.168
It paid off--
handsomely, I may add.

19:39.220 --> 19:41.971
Dan: When I engaged your services,
we entered into a partnership.

19:42.006 --> 19:44.974
William: Oh.
Did you see it that way?

19:45.009 --> 19:47.477
A partnership?
What? Like Virginia's and mine?

19:47.512 --> 19:48.978
Dan: No, actually,

19:49.013 --> 19:50.430
because I don't
make decisions unilaterally

19:50.482 --> 19:51.981
without her participation.

19:52.016 --> 19:54.267
William: Well,
perhaps you can clarify for me.

19:54.319 --> 19:56.853
Uh, what is the argument for,

19:56.905 --> 19:59.605
uh, perpetuating
this arrangement?

19:59.657 --> 20:03.192
Your venture into,
uh... lubricants?

20:03.244 --> 20:04.777
Dan: Lotions.

20:04.829 --> 20:06.446
William: Lotions.
I'm sorry. You're right.

20:06.498 --> 20:07.997
Alice:
There was a company in Seattle

20:08.032 --> 20:10.450
that Danny did
a lotion line with.

20:10.502 --> 20:13.252
He was working very closely
for many months

20:13.338 --> 20:15.371
with the most darling
Japanese chemist.

20:15.373 --> 20:17.373
What was her name-- Emiko?

20:17.425 --> 20:21.544
Virginia: I'm so sorry that you don't
consider our efforts worthwhile,

20:21.596 --> 20:24.464
but I have certainly
granted you latitude

20:24.516 --> 20:26.682
to pursue the things
you find interesting.

20:26.718 --> 20:28.151
Alice:
I thought the scent was lovely,

20:28.186 --> 20:29.886
but Dan didn't like me
to wear it.

20:29.938 --> 20:33.322
It's funny. He objects to me
wearing fragrance of any kind.

20:33.358 --> 20:35.191
Isn't that silly, Virginia?

20:35.226 --> 20:41.531
For a man in <i> his</i> line of work
to have... what's the word?

20:41.566 --> 20:42.832
An aversion?

20:42.867 --> 20:46.202
Dan: You know
what occurs to me, Bill?

20:46.237 --> 20:49.672
Is that you planned this dinner

20:49.707 --> 20:52.375
before you knew how the meeting
with your publisher was gonna go.

20:52.410 --> 20:55.578
William: Well,
it's like you said yourself--

20:55.630 --> 20:58.080
a positive outcome
was virtually assured.

20:58.082 --> 20:59.749
Our last book was
a best-seller.

20:59.801 --> 21:03.503
Dan: No, no. But then it means
you must've come prepared

21:03.555 --> 21:06.556
to offer up the surrogacy work
over Virginia's objections.

21:06.591 --> 21:09.225
Anything
to get your publisher on board

21:09.260 --> 21:12.178
so there would be cause
for celebration tonight

21:12.263 --> 21:15.731
and a reason to say to me,
"Thank you. Here's your hat.

21:15.767 --> 21:19.519
Don't let the door hit you
on the way out."

21:19.571 --> 21:21.771
Virginia:
Dan, Alice,

21:21.773 --> 21:24.607
I am so sorry
to have to cut this short.

21:24.659 --> 21:26.192
It was lovely to meet you.

21:26.244 --> 21:29.278
Alice: - You're leaving?
Virginia: - I'm afraid so.

21:29.280 --> 21:30.613
I knew there was a reason
I held on to my coat.

21:30.615 --> 21:32.081
Alice: You're sick?

21:32.116 --> 21:35.868
Virginia: Yes. Of him.
If you'll excuse me.

21:35.920 --> 21:38.287
William: - Virginia--
Virginia: - Go to hell.

21:38.289 --> 21:39.872
Libby: There's something
I need to talk to you about.

21:39.924 --> 21:44.760
It's about us
and about the future.

21:44.796 --> 21:48.047
[ Sighs ]

21:48.099 --> 21:50.967
Paul: It's okay.
It's a-- it's a good start.

21:51.002 --> 21:54.604
Libby: You don't think
it-- it feels too dire?

21:54.639 --> 21:57.056
I mean, maybe there's
a more casual way to get into it

21:57.108 --> 21:58.808
so Bill's not
immediately on his guard.

21:58.860 --> 22:00.476
Paul:
No, I don't-- I don't--

22:00.478 --> 22:02.278
I don't think the downbeat
is the problem, honey.

22:02.313 --> 22:05.514
I think you just need to be more
honest and be direct with him.

22:05.550 --> 22:07.016
Just tell him what you want.

22:07.051 --> 22:08.284
Libby: What do I want?

22:08.319 --> 22:09.785
Paul: Well...

22:09.821 --> 22:12.655
Libby: Do I-- do I ask
for a divorce right away,

22:12.657 --> 22:16.576
or do I want a separation first
and then a divorce?

22:16.628 --> 22:18.494
What do I say
when he asks me why?

22:18.496 --> 22:20.296
I mean,
he is gonna ask me why.

22:20.331 --> 22:25.251
Paul: Well, what if he does?
What are you gonna tell him?

22:25.303 --> 22:27.169
Libby: I don't want him to know
it's because of you.

22:27.222 --> 22:30.840
I-I think that just
makes it... harder.

22:30.842 --> 22:34.477
Paul: Well, look, you had many reasons
to leave him before me, right?

22:34.512 --> 22:37.813
- I mean...
Libby: - Yeah.

22:37.849 --> 22:39.982
Just not the courage.

22:40.018 --> 22:41.067
Paul: Right.

22:44.355 --> 22:47.440
Libby:
I think he'll be shocked.

22:47.492 --> 22:52.278
And then... maybe angry.

22:52.330 --> 22:53.996
I don't think he'll yell.

22:54.032 --> 22:58.334
I mean, he might, but... I think
he would be too scared

22:58.369 --> 23:00.336
that I would say something
about Virginia

23:00.371 --> 23:03.789
to ever accuse me of anything.

23:03.841 --> 23:05.007
No, what I'm...

23:06.344 --> 23:08.344
[ Sighs ]

23:08.379 --> 23:11.881
What I am most afraid of is...

23:15.937 --> 23:19.689
What if he doesn't care?

23:19.724 --> 23:21.223
You know?

23:21.276 --> 23:23.726
What if, when I tell him,

23:23.728 --> 23:29.065
I look in his eyes
and all I see is relief?

23:31.569 --> 23:32.868
[ Knock on door ]

23:38.777 --> 23:40.777
Can I help you?

23:40.829 --> 23:43.079
David: - Elizabeth Masters?
Libby: - Yes.

23:43.114 --> 23:46.616
David: I'm Detective David Ascher-- St.
Louis Police.

23:46.668 --> 23:49.318
Libby: - Has something happened?
David: - May I come in, please?

23:49.354 --> 23:51.587
[ Door closes ]

23:51.623 --> 23:52.855
Paul: What's going on?

23:52.891 --> 23:54.207
David: Dr. Masters?

23:54.259 --> 23:56.759
Paul: Um, no.

23:56.795 --> 23:58.461
Libby: This is Mr. Edley.

23:58.513 --> 24:02.331
Paul: Paul Edley.
I live next door. What's...?

24:02.367 --> 24:04.333
David: And Dr. Masters?
Is he home?

24:04.369 --> 24:07.637
Libby:
No, he's out of town.

24:07.689 --> 24:09.472
David: And your children?

24:09.524 --> 24:11.274
Libby:
My children are asleep.

24:11.309 --> 24:15.361
David: I need to ask your son
a few questions, Mrs. Masters.

24:15.397 --> 24:17.196
It won't take long.

24:17.232 --> 24:19.198
Libby:
Questions about what?

24:19.234 --> 24:20.850
Paul: You can't just knock on the
door in the middle of the night

24:20.885 --> 24:22.752
demanding to talk
to a 12-year-old child.

24:22.787 --> 24:25.421
David: I'm sorry, Mr. Edley,
but if you're not family,

24:25.457 --> 24:27.790
I need to ask you to leave.

24:27.826 --> 24:30.543
And, ma'am,
I need you to wake up your son.

24:33.064 --> 24:34.330
William: Virginia, I'm sorry.
Please, come back.

24:34.382 --> 24:35.631
Virginia: Get away from me.

24:35.667 --> 24:36.916
William: Please,
don't leave like this.

24:36.968 --> 24:39.001
Virginia: Dan was right.
You set me up.

24:39.054 --> 24:41.137
You knew that this was going to
happen before you left St. Louis.

24:41.172 --> 24:43.423
William: I can explain. Just let me
get my coat, and we'll go together.

24:43.475 --> 24:45.892
Virginia: Give that to me. You think
I'm going to get into a cab with you?

24:45.927 --> 24:47.343
William: Well, fine,
we'll go in separate cabs,

24:47.395 --> 24:49.145
but just at least let me
put you into one. Hello?

24:49.180 --> 24:50.763
Virginia: I can manage myself.
Give me back my purse, Bill.

24:50.815 --> 24:52.732
William: Just one second.
Hello? Can someone please...

24:52.767 --> 24:54.484
Virginia:
What were you thinking?

24:54.519 --> 24:56.102
What did you hope
to accomplish today?

24:56.154 --> 24:58.071
Or was it enough
to simply humiliate me?

24:58.106 --> 25:01.023
William:
I can't find my coat.

25:01.109 --> 25:04.277
Virginia: Here. Here!

25:04.329 --> 25:06.662
William:
Virginia, I-- I'm sorry.

25:06.698 --> 25:08.498
I didn't want it
to happen that way,

25:08.533 --> 25:09.966
but I needed you
to see for yourself.

25:10.001 --> 25:12.335
Virginia: See what?
That he has a wife?

25:12.370 --> 25:14.287
You think I didn't know that
already?

25:14.339 --> 25:16.172
William: You're not
his first affair, Virginia.

25:16.207 --> 25:17.840
You're just his most recent.

25:17.876 --> 25:20.460
Virginia: Well, that is <i> my</i>
problem to deal with, isn't it?

25:20.512 --> 25:21.928
William:
That doesn't bother you?

25:21.963 --> 25:24.464
Virginia: What I do
and whom I do it with

25:24.516 --> 25:27.467
outside of the office
is none of your business, Bill.

25:27.519 --> 25:29.051
William: Well,
you make it my business

25:29.053 --> 25:31.687
when you concoct some
ludicrous research program

25:31.723 --> 25:32.855
to keep that man
around our office.

25:32.891 --> 25:34.023
Lotions. Really?

25:34.058 --> 25:35.858
Virginia:
What choice did I have?

25:35.894 --> 25:38.144
The last time I was honest
with you about having a lover,

25:38.229 --> 25:40.530
you cut me out of the work
for a whole year.

25:40.565 --> 25:42.782
So either way,
whether I tell you or not,

25:42.867 --> 25:45.985
I end up in the exact same
place-- on the outside.

25:46.037 --> 25:47.904
Woman:
Excuse me. Number 36.

25:47.906 --> 25:50.239
It's a sable.

25:51.743 --> 25:54.143
David: Anything
you want to ask me first?

25:55.847 --> 25:58.181
Johnny:
Have you got a gun?

25:58.216 --> 26:00.817
David: I do.
You want to see it?

26:00.852 --> 26:03.136
Johnny: Sure.

26:03.171 --> 26:05.154
David: I've never fired it
in the line of duty, though.

26:05.190 --> 26:06.589
Johnny:
Have you fired it otherwise?

26:06.624 --> 26:07.857
David: Well,
not this particular one.

26:07.892 --> 26:10.760
I go hunting with my son
sometimes.

26:10.762 --> 26:13.262
He's about your age.

26:13.298 --> 26:15.731
Your dad ever take you hunting?

26:15.767 --> 26:17.667
Johnny: Not really.

26:17.702 --> 26:19.402
David: What kind of things
you and he like to do together?

26:19.437 --> 26:25.775
Johnny: Um, well, he,
uh-- he works a lot, so...

26:25.777 --> 26:28.644
David: Ah. Yeah.
Uh, what's he do?

26:28.680 --> 26:33.249
Johnny: - He's a doctor.
David: - What kind of doctor?

26:33.284 --> 26:36.352
Johnny: He teaches people
how to make babies

26:36.387 --> 26:41.257
and how to make their parts
fit together in the right way.

26:41.292 --> 26:43.159
David: "Their parts?"

26:43.194 --> 26:44.660
Libby: It's okay.

26:44.696 --> 26:46.629
Uh, my husband conducts
clinical research--

26:46.681 --> 26:47.964
David: I know what he does,
Mrs. Masters.

26:47.966 --> 26:50.466
I just want to hear
from your son.

26:50.518 --> 26:56.772
Johnny, has your dad ever
shown you how <i> your</i> body works?

26:56.808 --> 27:00.610
You know,
pointed things out to you.

27:00.645 --> 27:02.144
Like, uh,
when you're getting dressed

27:02.180 --> 27:04.614
or in the bathtub
or in the shower?

27:04.649 --> 27:07.049
Johnny: No.

27:07.085 --> 27:09.352
David: Has he ever shown you
how <i> his</i> body works?

27:09.387 --> 27:11.120
Libby: Of course he hasn't,
Detective.

27:11.155 --> 27:12.488
David:
Mrs. Masters, please.

27:12.490 --> 27:14.957
Johnny:
Of course he hasn't.

27:19.530 --> 27:22.381
David: Has he ever shown
any of your friends

27:22.417 --> 27:24.467
how <i> their</i> bodies work?

27:27.538 --> 27:29.372
Johnny: I don't know.

27:31.442 --> 27:34.310
David: You've never heard him
talk about those kind of things

27:34.345 --> 27:37.680
with any of your friends?

27:37.682 --> 27:41.234
Johnny:
With my friends? No.

27:41.269 --> 27:44.654
David:
Someone who's not your friend?

27:44.689 --> 27:47.390
This is very important, Johnny.

27:47.425 --> 27:49.358
Who has he talked to?

27:53.965 --> 27:55.631
Johnny: So,
once he talked to Dennis.

27:55.667 --> 27:57.750
Libby: Dennis Daughtry?

27:57.785 --> 28:00.202
David: And he talked to him
about his body?

28:00.204 --> 28:02.705
Libby: When was this?

28:02.707 --> 28:06.575
Johnny: Few weeks ago.
After the party for the team.

28:06.611 --> 28:08.127
Libby: Well, I was there.

28:08.179 --> 28:10.263
I-- I didn't see your father
talking to Dennis.

28:10.298 --> 28:13.282
Johnny:
You were putting Howie to bed.

28:13.318 --> 28:15.885
Dennis was waiting
for his mom to pick him up.

28:15.887 --> 28:17.253
That's what he said.

28:17.288 --> 28:19.755
David: And what did you hear
them talking about?

28:19.791 --> 28:22.491
Johnny: - I don't remember.
David: - You don't remember

28:22.527 --> 28:26.162
what you told Martha Geiss and
Olive Lambert on the playground?

28:29.300 --> 28:30.733
Johnny: No.

28:30.785 --> 28:32.401
David: Because they said
you told them something

28:32.453 --> 28:35.121
about Dennis and your father.

28:35.156 --> 28:37.773
Libby: What did you tell them,
Johnny?

28:37.809 --> 28:39.108
It's okay.

28:39.143 --> 28:40.876
David:
You don't remember saying

28:40.912 --> 28:44.580
that your father had to show
Dennis how to fix his penis?

28:44.615 --> 28:46.749
Libby: What?
What?

28:46.751 --> 28:48.517
Johnny: Yes, but...

28:48.553 --> 28:54.590
I didn't mean-- I just-- I
just said that 'cause I was mad.

28:54.592 --> 28:55.825
David:
And why were you mad?

28:55.860 --> 28:58.594
Johnny:
Because I hate that kid.

28:58.596 --> 28:59.829
He's an asshole.

28:59.864 --> 29:02.315
Libby: Johnny.

29:02.350 --> 29:04.317
Johnny: And-- and dad's
always so nice to him.

29:04.352 --> 29:05.484
David:
How is he nice to him?

29:05.520 --> 29:08.354
Johnny:
He just is. He...

29:08.406 --> 29:13.142
He talks to him...
Spends time with him.

29:13.177 --> 29:14.977
David:
Spends time with him

29:15.013 --> 29:16.979
in ways that are different than
the way he spends time with you?

29:17.015 --> 29:18.647
Johnny:
He doesn't spend time with me.

29:18.683 --> 29:20.282
Libby:
That's not true, Johnny.

29:20.335 --> 29:23.285
Johnny:
He likes Dennis more.

29:23.287 --> 29:25.705
Libby: - No, sweetheart.
David: - Mrs. Masters.

29:25.757 --> 29:29.759
Johnny... I need to know.

29:29.794 --> 29:32.378
Have you ever seen
your father and Dennis

29:32.430 --> 29:34.230
have any kind
of physical contact--

29:34.265 --> 29:35.598
Libby: Okay,
that is enough, Detective.

29:35.633 --> 29:36.882
David:
I am not done here, ma'am.

29:36.934 --> 29:38.551
Libby: Yes,
I would say you are done.

29:38.603 --> 29:40.186
I am not gonna subject my child
to any more of this.

29:40.221 --> 29:41.904
David: I can bring him
down to the station

29:41.939 --> 29:43.556
- if that's what you prefer.
Libby: - Do not threaten me, sir.

29:43.608 --> 29:45.391
- Johnny, I need you to go to y--
Johnny: - I'm sorry.

29:45.443 --> 29:46.809
Libby: It's okay. It's okay.
You didn't do anything wrong.

29:46.861 --> 29:47.877
Johnny: I'm sorry.

29:47.912 --> 29:49.195
Libby: No one's mad at you,
honey.

29:49.230 --> 29:50.696
I just need a few minutes alone
with the detective.

29:50.732 --> 29:52.365
Johnny: - But, mom--
Libby: - It's okay. Please go.

29:52.400 --> 29:55.735
I'll be in in a second
to tuck you in. Go on. Go on.

29:56.621 --> 29:59.655
[ Bedroom door closes ]

29:59.657 --> 30:01.574
I don't know what you think
is going on here.

30:01.626 --> 30:05.044
I don't know who said what, if
some silly girl on a playground

30:05.079 --> 30:07.413
twisted my son's words to make
it seem like my husband--

30:07.465 --> 30:09.415
David: The boy confirmed
with his mother

30:09.467 --> 30:13.202
that your husband showed him
pictures of a naked man.

30:13.237 --> 30:15.921
Libby:
My husband is a doctor.

30:15.973 --> 30:18.507
If he showed that boy
images in a medical textbook,

30:18.559 --> 30:21.177
I am sure there is a perfectly
reasonable explanation for it.

30:21.179 --> 30:22.812
David:
Without his mother's knowledge?

30:22.847 --> 30:24.814
Libby: [ Scoffs ]
I would say any mother

30:24.849 --> 30:27.650
who leaves her son at a party
isn't fit to judge.

30:27.685 --> 30:30.986
David: Mrs. Masters, can you
tell me the circumstances

30:31.022 --> 30:35.524
under which an adult showing
a minor explicit sexual images

30:35.576 --> 30:37.860
can be considered
appropriate behavior?

30:40.665 --> 30:43.165
Libby: My husband
would never hurt a child.

30:43.201 --> 30:46.502
David: And yet it sounds to me
as if he's hurt your son.

30:46.537 --> 30:48.537
Libby:
You need to leave, Detective.

30:48.589 --> 30:49.839
David: That's fine.

30:49.874 --> 30:52.174
I will have to follow up,
of course.

30:52.210 --> 30:55.878
Libby: And when you do,
our lawyer will be present.

31:02.120 --> 31:04.854
Dan: Hmm. Well,
let's get our check, shall we?

31:04.889 --> 31:06.322
Alice:
We barely just ordered.

31:06.357 --> 31:08.824
Dan: I think this dinner's over,
wouldn't you say?

31:08.860 --> 31:10.226
Alice:
I don't want to go.

31:10.311 --> 31:11.444
Dan: - Alice, come on.
Alice: - You can go.

31:11.479 --> 31:12.895
Dan: Alice.

31:12.947 --> 31:14.980
Alice: Are you not hearing me?
I'm staying.

31:15.032 --> 31:16.148
Do you want me to make a scene?

31:21.289 --> 31:23.572
Dan: [ Sighs ]

31:23.574 --> 31:26.008
You want to finish the bottle.
That's it, isn't it?

31:26.043 --> 31:28.160
So how long have you
managed to go this time?

31:28.212 --> 31:29.662
Three months?

31:29.714 --> 31:31.947
Alice: I'll go to a meeting
in the morning.

31:31.983 --> 31:35.151
I'm sorry.

31:35.186 --> 31:37.520
Dan: - You're not.
Alice: - Are <i> you</i> sorry?

31:37.555 --> 31:39.522
Dan: Yes, I am.

31:39.557 --> 31:41.757
Alice: For being with her,
or for rubbing my face in it?

31:41.759 --> 31:43.843
Dan: You know I wouldn't have chosen
for you to find out this way.

31:43.895 --> 31:46.095
Alice: Is there a good way
to meet your husband's mistress?

31:46.097 --> 31:47.730
Can't you even pretend?

31:47.765 --> 31:50.266
Dan: I've never denied
I was with any of them, Alice.

31:50.268 --> 31:53.369
I've always been straight
with you.

31:53.404 --> 31:54.904
You can't claim it's unfair

31:54.939 --> 31:56.322
when it was you
who proposed this arrangement.

31:56.357 --> 31:58.240
Alice:
What choice did I have?

31:58.276 --> 31:59.775
Dan: Alice, I don't want
to do this here. Let's go.

31:59.777 --> 32:01.994
Alice: I'm asking.

32:02.029 --> 32:04.914
What choice did you leave me
with but to look the other way?

32:04.949 --> 32:06.348
Dan: You do not want
to go down this road. Trust me.

32:06.384 --> 32:08.951
Alice: Oh, why not?

32:09.003 --> 32:10.336
Dan:
Because you don't think

32:10.371 --> 32:12.321
your behavior leaves me
without a choice?

32:12.356 --> 32:14.256
Every time you disappear
down that bottle

32:14.292 --> 32:15.524
and I have to come find you

32:15.560 --> 32:17.159
or you threaten
to hurt yourself.

32:17.195 --> 32:19.628
Alice:
It brings you back.

32:19.630 --> 32:21.263
Admit it, you like fixing me.

32:21.299 --> 32:23.966
Dan: I used to.

32:23.968 --> 32:27.303
Can't say I've done such
a good job of it lately, have I?

32:27.305 --> 32:29.889
Alice: You always like the ones
that need fixing.

32:31.809 --> 32:34.276
Tell me.
How is this one broken?

32:35.279 --> 32:37.413
Dan: She's not.

32:37.448 --> 32:41.567
Alice: Come on. What is it?
Financial problems?

32:41.619 --> 32:45.404
Childhood abuse? An
ex-husband who's stalking her?

32:45.456 --> 32:48.073
Dan:
Virginia's different.

32:48.125 --> 32:51.627
Alice: They're all different
until they're all the same.

32:55.366 --> 32:57.466
Dan:
I'm in love with her, Alice.

33:00.137 --> 33:03.839
Now, you've never heard me
say that before.

33:03.891 --> 33:07.009
Virginia: What kind of
partnership do we have, Bill,

33:07.061 --> 33:10.613
if you marginalize me
every time I've upset you?

33:10.648 --> 33:14.683
How are we equals if you're
always able to exact a price

33:14.735 --> 33:17.486
for me wanting something
outside of work?

33:17.521 --> 33:19.688
William: I know you're angry,
and rightly so,

33:19.740 --> 33:22.408
but eventually you will see
that this is for the best.

33:22.443 --> 33:24.260
I am saving you from that man.

33:24.295 --> 33:28.364
Virginia: "That man" is someone
that I could be happy with.

33:28.416 --> 33:30.616
William: I-I really don't
think so, Virginia.

33:30.668 --> 33:32.201
Virginia:
And-- and why is that?

33:32.203 --> 33:34.286
Because of the kind of man
you <i> think</i> he is,

33:34.338 --> 33:36.939
or because I'm just not entitled
to a life outside of work?

33:36.974 --> 33:38.874
William: You're--
you're entitled to one.

33:38.876 --> 33:39.925
You just don't want one.

33:41.963 --> 33:43.212
Virginia:
That was the argument

33:43.214 --> 33:44.680
that you made to me
in the hospital,

33:44.715 --> 33:46.181
when I was in labor,

33:46.217 --> 33:50.019
that-- that my ambivalence
is the problem,

33:50.054 --> 33:52.354
that I should embrace
the part of me

33:52.390 --> 33:54.223
that cares about work
above all else.

33:54.225 --> 33:58.360
Hell, I thought you meant that.

34:00.147 --> 34:03.666
But I see now the person that
argument really serves is you,

34:03.701 --> 34:06.819
that you were just
looking out for yourself.

34:06.871 --> 34:09.655
You're always just
looking out for yourself.

34:10.908 --> 34:12.908
Alice:
Why do you love her?

34:15.478 --> 34:16.712
Dan: Ally--

34:16.746 --> 34:20.382
Alice: Tell me.
I promise I won't get mad.

34:20.418 --> 34:22.751
Dan: [ Sighs ]

34:22.803 --> 34:25.420
There's no easy way
to explain it. I--

34:25.422 --> 34:29.174
Alice: It's okay.
Just tell me as a favor to me.

34:31.762 --> 34:33.929
Dan: Well, for one,

34:33.981 --> 34:36.598
her life doesn't start
when I arrive

34:36.600 --> 34:38.350
and stop when I leave.

34:39.270 --> 34:40.601
She has other things
she cares about.

34:40.603 --> 34:42.071
I'm not her whole world.

34:42.106 --> 34:43.989
Alice: - That's a good thing?
Dan: - Yes, it is.

34:44.025 --> 34:46.275
Alice: Why?

34:46.327 --> 34:47.609
Dan: [ Sighs ]

34:47.610 --> 34:51.112
Alice: It's okay.
I know.

34:53.284 --> 34:55.784
You need a partner,
not a project.

34:55.786 --> 34:59.788
And I'm a project.

34:59.790 --> 35:03.876
But I wasn't always.

35:03.928 --> 35:06.211
Was I?

35:13.888 --> 35:15.938
Does she make you laugh?

35:18.392 --> 35:20.025
Dan: Yes.

35:28.903 --> 35:31.487
Alice:
I used to make you laugh.

35:31.489 --> 35:34.239
Dan:
You still do make me laugh.

35:34.325 --> 35:36.542
Alice:
[ Crying ] But not enough

35:36.577 --> 35:38.260
to make up
for all the other stuff.

35:38.295 --> 35:41.830
[ Sighs ]

35:41.882 --> 35:43.298
Jacques:
Madame and monsieur,

35:43.334 --> 35:47.169
prepared especially for you,
steak tartare.

35:47.221 --> 35:49.271
Bon appétit.

35:49.306 --> 35:53.392
William: You think I want to
keep you tethered to your desk?

35:53.427 --> 35:55.010
I said what I did

35:55.062 --> 35:57.179
because you needed permission
to stop hating yourself.

35:57.181 --> 36:00.516
Virginia: - I don't hate myself.
William: - No?

36:00.568 --> 36:02.851
You want to want a man,
Virginia,

36:02.903 --> 36:05.687
because, as unconventional
as you consider yourself,

36:05.740 --> 36:07.022
you're still
your mother's daughter,

36:07.024 --> 36:09.408
and she told you
you need one to be happy.

36:09.443 --> 36:10.993
But I know you.

36:11.028 --> 36:12.828
A relationship
will never satisfy you

36:12.863 --> 36:14.630
the way your work will.

36:14.665 --> 36:17.032
It lights you up.

36:17.084 --> 36:19.835
It gives you a purpose
so much more consequential

36:19.870 --> 36:21.787
than waiting
for a man to come home.

36:21.839 --> 36:23.372
And-- and what?

36:23.424 --> 36:25.541
Check his collar to see
if there's lipstick on it?

36:25.593 --> 36:28.710
That is too small a life
for you, Virginia,

36:28.763 --> 36:32.347
and it is a waste of what
you have to offer the world.

36:32.383 --> 36:33.966
Rog: Excuse me.

36:34.018 --> 36:36.351
By any chance, are you those
people from the sex book?

36:36.387 --> 36:38.187
Woman:
Masters and Johnson, right?

36:38.222 --> 36:40.189
Rog: We just loved your book.
Uh, if there's any way, uh--

36:40.224 --> 36:42.141
Woman: Oh, Rog and I would just
be so tickled if we could just--

36:42.193 --> 36:43.559
Rog: If we could just
get an autograph.

36:43.561 --> 36:46.228
William: - I'm sorry.
Colette: - Excuse me.

36:46.230 --> 36:48.564
Alice: - [ Crying ]
Dan: - Alice.

36:48.616 --> 36:50.232
Virginia:
Dan, what is it?

36:50.234 --> 36:52.234
Dan:
She's not feeling well.

36:52.286 --> 36:54.703
Virginia: I'll go.

36:54.738 --> 36:57.706
Maitre D': Will there be any
more comings and goings tonight,

36:57.741 --> 37:01.243
or may we serve you
your dinner?

37:01.245 --> 37:02.678
Johnny: Are they gonna
put him in jail?

37:02.713 --> 37:05.013
Libby:
No. Of course not.

37:05.049 --> 37:06.715
Johnny:
But he'll find out, won't he,

37:06.750 --> 37:09.668
that-- that I said the thing
that got him in trouble?

37:09.720 --> 37:11.136
Libby: It's not about
what you said, Johnny.

37:11.172 --> 37:12.671
It's about how people
took what you said.

37:12.723 --> 37:14.089
And they will come to see

37:14.091 --> 37:16.175
that dad was just being nice
to that boy.

37:16.227 --> 37:19.061
Johnny: Yeah, but
he's-- he's gonna know

37:19.096 --> 37:22.264
that I started it,
and it's just...

37:22.316 --> 37:25.267
It's gonna give him
another reason to hate me.

37:27.438 --> 37:29.404
Libby:
Your father doesn't hate you.

37:29.440 --> 37:31.440
Johnny:
He doesn't like me.

37:31.525 --> 37:33.609
Libby:
What are you talking about?

37:33.611 --> 37:36.712
Johnny,
your father loves you.

37:36.747 --> 37:39.848
Johnny: You're always telling
dad to spend more time with me.

37:39.884 --> 37:43.368
If he wanted to,
you wouldn't have to ask.

37:48.959 --> 37:52.377
Libby:
Can I tell you a little secret?

37:52.429 --> 37:55.013
[ Sniffles ]

37:55.049 --> 37:57.266
I think
your father is afraid of you.

37:57.301 --> 37:59.701
Johnny: Afraid of me?

37:59.737 --> 38:02.638
Libby: Of showing you
how much he loves you.

38:05.476 --> 38:09.862
Johnny: - I don't think so.
Libby: - No.

38:09.897 --> 38:12.397
When you were a little baby,

38:12.449 --> 38:16.702
he was scared to hold you,
because...

38:16.737 --> 38:18.487
[ Sighs ]

38:18.489 --> 38:23.242
Well, because I think
he was afraid

38:23.294 --> 38:28.330
to love something
he might hurt.

38:28.332 --> 38:33.585
You were so perfect
that he didn't want to ruin you.

38:33.637 --> 38:35.304
[ Sniffles ]

38:35.339 --> 38:38.590
Johnny:
How would he do that?

38:38.642 --> 38:41.927
Libby:
By... passing on to you

38:41.979 --> 38:45.814
the things
he doesn't like about himself.

38:45.849 --> 38:48.684
Johnny: Like what?

38:48.686 --> 38:51.019
Libby: I don't know.
[ Sniffles ]

38:51.021 --> 38:54.323
Maybe things that he feels like
he got from his father.

38:54.358 --> 38:58.744
Dad didn't, uh--
didn't like his father.

38:58.779 --> 39:00.362
Johnny: Why not?

39:02.366 --> 39:09.371
Libby: Uh... he didn't think
his father liked <i> him</i> very much.

39:09.423 --> 39:13.926
Johnny:
Why? What did he do?

39:13.961 --> 39:17.512
Libby: I don't think he cared
about being a good father.

39:17.548 --> 39:19.965
He was an angry man,

39:20.017 --> 39:21.850
and he didn't know
what to do with his anger,

39:21.885 --> 39:28.807
so it came out in ways
that hurt daddy.

39:28.859 --> 39:31.193
Which is why
he left home so early.

39:31.228 --> 39:34.279
He was not much older
than you.

39:34.315 --> 39:37.399
Johnny:
So they never made up?

39:37.401 --> 39:41.820
They were just... mad
at each other forever

39:41.872 --> 39:45.824
and then just
never-- never made up?

39:49.380 --> 39:52.748
I was hoping it'd be better
between dad and me someday.

39:55.135 --> 39:57.386
What if I ruined that?

39:57.421 --> 40:00.589
Libby: Oh, honey,
of course you didn't.

40:00.591 --> 40:03.675
Of course you didn't.
[ Sniffles ]

40:03.727 --> 40:05.560
[ Sighs ]

40:08.632 --> 40:10.565
Alice: [ Sighs ]

40:10.601 --> 40:12.234
Virginia:
Are you all right?

40:12.269 --> 40:15.604
Alice: [ Sighs ]
The room is spinning.

40:15.656 --> 40:17.656
[ Sniffles ]

40:17.691 --> 40:19.408
Virginia: Come sit.

40:19.443 --> 40:22.744
Alice: Okay.
Thank you.

40:22.780 --> 40:25.981
Virginia: - A wet towel, please?
Daphne: - Yes.

40:26.016 --> 40:27.866
[ Water running ]

40:31.121 --> 40:32.287
[ Water stops ]

40:34.091 --> 40:35.590
Virginia: Thank you.

40:35.626 --> 40:37.542
Daphne: May I offer you
some mouthwash, ma'am?

40:37.594 --> 40:38.960
Alice: [ Sniffles ]
Yes, thank you.

40:39.013 --> 40:40.462
Daphne: Um...

40:40.464 --> 40:44.633
Alice:
Ugh, what a disaster.

40:44.635 --> 40:48.270
You weren't there
when the steak tartare arrived.

40:48.305 --> 40:52.074
It was the three glistening
egg yolks on top that did it.

40:52.109 --> 40:53.675
Virginia: Ugh, God.

40:53.711 --> 40:55.444
Daphne:
Do either of you ladies know

40:55.479 --> 40:59.231
if "E-Yew De-Toilet"
is mouthwash?

40:59.283 --> 41:03.368
Virginia: Uh... perhaps
you could, uh, get my friend

41:03.404 --> 41:05.253
a soft drink from the bar.

41:05.289 --> 41:07.122
Daphne: Okay.

41:07.157 --> 41:08.990
[ Door opens ]

41:09.043 --> 41:12.160
Alice: Actually, we could've
been friends, you and I.

41:12.162 --> 41:13.745
[ Door closes ]

41:13.797 --> 41:15.747
Virginia: Can't we still?

41:15.799 --> 41:17.215
Alice: [ Chuckles ]

41:17.251 --> 41:20.001
I think it's a little awkward,
don't you,

41:20.003 --> 41:23.271
seeing as how my husband's
in love with you?

41:23.307 --> 41:24.840
Virginia: [ Scoffs ]

41:24.892 --> 41:27.175
Alice: Don't insult me
by acting surprised.

41:27.227 --> 41:30.178
Danny told me.

41:30.230 --> 41:32.514
Virginia:
He-- he told you...

41:32.516 --> 41:37.853
Alice: He always tells me.
We've been through this before.

41:37.855 --> 41:40.522
Did you think
you were different?

41:40.524 --> 41:44.726
They all do.

41:44.762 --> 41:48.330
Enjoy him, Virginia.

41:48.365 --> 41:51.867
He's a lovely man.

41:51.869 --> 41:54.970
A true gentleman.

41:55.005 --> 41:58.540
He'll always
open the door for you,

41:58.542 --> 42:01.710
he'll never
forget your birthday,

42:01.712 --> 42:05.013
whisk you away
on business trips,

42:05.048 --> 42:07.382
and take you in his arms
and dance with you

42:07.384 --> 42:09.384
even though
there's no music playing.

42:12.439 --> 42:15.290
And when he shows up
at your doorstep

42:15.359 --> 42:20.896
and tells you that he wants you to
spend the rest of your life with him,

42:20.948 --> 42:25.617
in that moment,
he will think he means it.

42:30.991 --> 42:32.741
Libby: I didn't know
what to say to him.

42:32.793 --> 42:36.044
Of course, he completely
blames himself.

42:36.079 --> 42:37.579
Paul: Well, are-- are
charges gonna be filed?

42:37.631 --> 42:39.080
Libby: I don't know.

42:39.133 --> 42:40.632
Paul: What,
the detective didn't say, or--

42:40.667 --> 42:43.084
Libby: No, Paul, I told you.
It ended abruptly.

42:43.086 --> 42:44.252
I-I asked him to leave.

42:46.757 --> 42:49.257
Paul: And what did Johnny
tell you actually happened?

42:49.309 --> 42:52.594
Libby: Tell me?
Nothing. I didn't ask.

42:52.646 --> 42:55.864
Paul: You didn't ask him
to elaborate on what he saw?

42:55.899 --> 42:59.100
Libby: Why would I?

42:59.102 --> 43:01.269
This is just
a-a misunderstanding

43:01.271 --> 43:02.487
that's gotten out of hand.

43:02.523 --> 43:03.989
It's-- it's Bill's work

43:04.024 --> 43:06.358
that makes him vulnerable
to accusations like this.

43:06.410 --> 43:09.361
Paul: Well, it's his work and
his lack of judgment, I think.

43:09.413 --> 43:11.363
Libby:
You don't seriously think--

43:12.616 --> 43:16.201
No, he didn't do anything wrong.
I know that. For sure.

43:16.286 --> 43:18.703
I know what kind of man
my husband is.

43:18.755 --> 43:21.673
Paul:
Well, he's the kind of man

43:21.708 --> 43:24.926
who-- who's had a mistress
for over a decade.

43:24.962 --> 43:27.762
Libby: Yeah, but that's
something he did to me, Paul.

43:27.798 --> 43:29.965
He-- he wouldn't
hurt a child.

43:29.967 --> 43:32.133
Never.

43:32.135 --> 43:34.853
Paul: I woke up every morning
for a decade

43:34.888 --> 43:36.471
thinking that
I was a happily married man.

43:36.473 --> 43:38.974
All the while, my wife
was planning on leaving me.

43:38.976 --> 43:42.727
You think you know someone,
and you don't.

43:42.779 --> 43:47.816
You have to get out. Now.
Before Bill comes home.

43:47.818 --> 43:49.534
I'll look into
renting you a house

43:49.570 --> 43:51.486
for you and the kids
across town.

43:54.992 --> 43:57.525
Libby:
I can't do that, Paul.

43:57.561 --> 43:59.878
Paul:
You can't do what?

43:59.913 --> 44:02.881
You can't take steps
to protect your children?

44:02.916 --> 44:05.000
Libby: [ Sighs ]

44:10.974 --> 44:15.894
[ Voice breaking ]
I am protecting them...

44:15.929 --> 44:20.599
from the false impression
that their father is a monster.

44:20.651 --> 44:24.185
Because, if I leave now,
that is what I am saying.

44:24.187 --> 44:27.355
Not just to the world,
but to my children.

44:27.357 --> 44:30.525
And there's no taking it back.

44:30.577 --> 44:32.527
No matter what happens,

44:32.529 --> 44:35.196
no matter if
the charges are dropped,

44:35.198 --> 44:36.581
he will forever be the man

44:36.617 --> 44:40.418
their mother didn't want
under the same roof.

44:40.454 --> 44:42.704
Paul: Won't leaving Bill
always say to them

44:42.706 --> 44:45.640
that you think that
you're better off without him?

44:45.676 --> 44:48.710
Libby: Yes.

44:48.712 --> 44:52.213
Better for me.

44:52.299 --> 44:54.215
He has been a bad husband--
Bill.

44:54.268 --> 44:57.052
I have reasons to leave him
that are a mile long,

44:57.054 --> 45:00.221
but... I don't have
good enough reason

45:00.223 --> 45:02.607
to take those children
away from him.

45:02.643 --> 45:04.609
Paul: Because he's been
such a great father.

45:04.645 --> 45:06.061
[ Sighs ]

45:06.113 --> 45:09.130
I'd be a better one, Libby.
You know that.

45:13.453 --> 45:17.622
Libby: It doesn't matter.
It doesn't matter.

45:17.658 --> 45:20.659
He is the father
that they have.

45:20.711 --> 45:26.081
He is the father that
Johnny needs to know loves him.

45:26.133 --> 45:27.716
Because-- because,
without that,

45:27.751 --> 45:32.587
it just-- it just plays out
in exactly the same way.

45:32.639 --> 45:34.839
Another son without a father

45:34.891 --> 45:41.313
becomes a father who doesn't
know how to love his son.

45:41.348 --> 45:44.265
And if...

45:44.318 --> 45:50.939
If I stay, they have a chance
to fix what is broken.

45:50.991 --> 45:53.742
Paul:
Libby, are you, um...

45:53.777 --> 45:58.747
Are you saying that this
is what you need to do now,

45:58.782 --> 46:00.365
for the time being,

46:00.417 --> 46:04.252
or what you need to do
forever?

46:12.596 --> 46:13.962
Jacques: Is there nothing
I can get you?

46:14.014 --> 46:15.263
William: Just the check,
thank you.

46:15.298 --> 46:16.498
Jacques: <i> Alain,</i>
<i>annulez la commande.</i>

46:16.533 --> 46:17.999
Alain: <i> On annule tout?</i>

46:18.035 --> 46:19.017
<i>Mais j'étais sur le point</i>
<i>de servir!</i>

46:19.052 --> 46:20.468
Jacques: <i> Oui, je sais.</i>

46:20.520 --> 46:21.970
<i>N'en dites pas un mot au chef.</i>

46:22.022 --> 46:25.523
<i>- Amenez l'addition, vite.</i>
<i>- D'accord.</i>

46:25.559 --> 46:27.976
Right away, monsieur.

46:27.978 --> 46:30.145
Dan:
So, I have to ask.

46:30.147 --> 46:34.149
How exactly did you expect
things to go tonight?

46:34.151 --> 46:36.818
William:
Just the way they did.

46:36.820 --> 46:40.355
Dan: Really?
With Virginia storming out?

46:40.390 --> 46:43.625
William:
Well, I saw her, uh, leaving

46:43.660 --> 46:46.327
a little closer to dessert,
but yes.

46:46.329 --> 46:49.998
Dan: Alice's presence helped
speeding up her departure?

46:50.000 --> 46:51.800
William: I'd say,
in the grand scheme of things,

46:51.835 --> 46:54.002
your wife's upset was a little
more your doing than mine,

46:54.004 --> 46:56.471
wouldn't you?

46:56.506 --> 46:58.339
Dan:
You're a son of a bitch, Bill.

46:58.341 --> 47:02.677
And a misguided one if you think
that alienating Virginia

47:02.729 --> 47:04.763
is the way to win her back.

47:04.815 --> 47:07.782
That is your end game,
isn't it?

47:07.818 --> 47:12.854
Or are you afraid admitting that
will give me an edge?

47:12.889 --> 47:15.290
William:
An edge?

47:16.526 --> 47:17.892
I'm sorry.

47:17.928 --> 47:20.412
I-- I hate to be the one
to break it to you, Dan,

47:20.447 --> 47:23.698
but she's finished with you.

47:23.700 --> 47:26.835
Uh, it may not happen right
away, but it-- it's inevitable.

47:26.870 --> 47:28.253
- It's over.
Dan: - Mm.

47:28.288 --> 47:29.537
And how do you figure?

47:29.573 --> 47:33.091
William: Well, because
that's what Virginia does.

47:33.126 --> 47:37.378
She never mentioned the name
Ethan Haas to you?

47:37.380 --> 47:41.015
He was a doctor.
Promising future.

47:41.051 --> 47:43.551
Would've done anything
for her,

47:43.603 --> 47:45.653
including walking away
from another woman.

47:45.689 --> 47:49.591
Virginia called the whole thing
off a few days before

47:49.626 --> 47:51.759
she was supposed to join him
in Los Angeles.

47:51.795 --> 47:54.863
Broke his heart, poor fellow.

47:54.898 --> 47:56.898
But I'm sure yours
is more resilient.

47:56.950 --> 47:58.066
Dan: So you're saying

47:58.118 --> 48:00.335
she changed her mind
completely on her own

48:00.370 --> 48:02.570
with no interference
from you?

48:02.572 --> 48:05.206
William: Oh, no,
I asked her to marry me.

48:05.242 --> 48:08.409
Only, uh, it wasn't on bended
knee with a ring in my pocket,

48:08.411 --> 48:10.295
if that's what
you're imagining.

48:10.330 --> 48:12.714
No, the marriage
I proposed to her

48:12.749 --> 48:15.967
was a marriage of the mind,
a true intellectual partnership,

48:16.002 --> 48:18.470
and I did it
without uttering a word.

48:18.505 --> 48:21.506
All I did was
put her name next to mine

48:21.558 --> 48:26.261
on that, uh, first paper
we presented at Wash U.

48:26.263 --> 48:28.263
It was my vow to her,
you know,

48:28.265 --> 48:34.569
that that was who we would
become-- Masters and Johnson.

48:34.604 --> 48:37.021
It's who we are.

48:37.073 --> 48:38.940
You know,
it's how people think of us.

48:38.942 --> 48:42.143
It's how we think of ourselves.
Virginia, too.

48:42.179 --> 48:44.679
Dan: Hm.
And that was 10 years ago.

48:44.714 --> 48:46.881
The bloom is off the rose.

48:46.917 --> 48:49.250
William: Hm. Perhaps.

48:49.286 --> 48:51.886
Which is why I've decided
to give her my name.

48:51.922 --> 48:55.590
Just my name--
no "MD" after it--

48:55.625 --> 48:59.093
and put it together with hers
on the next book.

48:59.129 --> 49:01.763
Kind of a renewal
of our vows.

49:01.798 --> 49:05.266
Dan: And you think that's gonna
make a difference?

49:05.302 --> 49:08.136
It's a little too late.
You've pushed her too far, no?

49:08.138 --> 49:10.221
William:
Well, in my experience,

49:10.273 --> 49:12.774
when the train
is pulling out of the station

49:12.809 --> 49:15.810
and you're not on it,
you run twice as fast

49:15.862 --> 49:19.147
and twice as hard to make sure
it doesn't leave without you.

49:22.152 --> 49:24.786
Dan: I bet you're damn good
at chess, Bill.

49:26.990 --> 49:28.356
And if we played,

49:28.391 --> 49:30.825
you'd probably have
the whole game figured out

49:30.877 --> 49:33.628
before I even made
my opening gambit.

49:33.663 --> 49:37.065
William:
It's quite possible.

49:37.100 --> 49:41.336
Dan: Mm. All this strategizing,
it's exhausting.

49:41.388 --> 49:44.105
You must be really tired.

49:44.140 --> 49:45.773
Plotting every move,

49:45.809 --> 49:48.509
anticipating every countermove
so far into the future

49:48.562 --> 49:50.228
that you completely lose sight

49:50.263 --> 49:54.682
that there's a far easier way
to get what you want.

49:54.734 --> 49:57.318
William: Which is what?

49:57.354 --> 49:59.821
Dan: Tell her
how you feel about her.

50:02.626 --> 50:05.526
But I bet that never
occurred to you, did it, Bill?

50:07.764 --> 50:13.368
Well, guess what.
It occurred to me.

50:13.403 --> 50:17.839
So, I guess
that's... checkmate?

50:19.576 --> 50:21.576
Maitre d':
I'm sorry to interrupt.

50:21.611 --> 50:24.045
There's a call for you
from St. Louis, Dr. Masters.

50:24.080 --> 50:26.314
They said it's an emergency.

50:34.891 --> 50:37.225
William: Well,
what time is the flight?

50:37.260 --> 50:38.893
It's about an hour and a half.

50:38.895 --> 50:40.561
Dan: You all right?

50:40.563 --> 50:43.564
Virginia: She's a little shaky.
You should get her home.

50:43.566 --> 50:45.783
Dan: Car's out front.

50:45.819 --> 50:47.619
Alice: Okay.

50:47.654 --> 50:50.805
Bill: I'll take a cab to the airport
as soon as possible.

50:53.810 --> 50:55.326
Dan:
Good night, Virginia.

51:01.751 --> 51:04.585
William: That was Betty.
Uh, Libby had to track me down.

51:04.638 --> 51:07.422
Something's happened.
I need to get home.

51:07.507 --> 51:09.507
Virginia:
What is it? The kids?

51:09.559 --> 51:10.642
William: I don't know.

51:10.677 --> 51:12.644
Uh, Betty didn't
have the details,

51:12.679 --> 51:14.796
but she has me booked on a flight
that leaves in 90 minutes.

51:14.831 --> 51:16.681
Virginia: Do you need me
to come with you?

51:16.733 --> 51:19.767
William: No, no.
We left our things in the hotel.

51:19.819 --> 51:22.537
You should stay the night
and bring them home with you.

51:22.572 --> 51:24.155
Virginia: All right.

51:24.190 --> 51:25.640
William: Virginia, I...

51:27.544 --> 51:30.311
I-I want you to know that, uh--

51:30.347 --> 51:32.864
Virginia:
This is not the time, Bill.

51:32.916 --> 51:34.449
Maitre D':
We have a cab for you, sir.

51:34.501 --> 51:37.201
[ <i> "Les Yeux Ouverts"</i> plays ]

51:37.253 --> 51:38.703
Virginia: Go.

51:43.193 --> 51:45.326
Maitre D':
Excuse me, madam.

51:45.362 --> 51:48.096
May we serve you
your dinner?

51:53.186 --> 51:55.553
Virginia: - All right.
Maitre D': - Very good, madam.

51:55.605 --> 51:57.889
Jacques, uh,
please seat madame

51:57.941 --> 51:59.874
and tell the kitchen
to resume service.

51:59.909 --> 52:02.360
May I?

52:07.150 --> 52:08.516
Virginia: Thank you.

